    <h2>Complete Jitter Clicking Guide for Beginners</h2>
    <p>Jitter clicking is one of the most popular clicking techniques in competitive gaming — especially in Minecraft PvP. It can more than double your CPS compared to regular clicking, but it takes real practice to learn. This guide covers everything from the basic technique to advanced tips for consistent performance.</p>

    <h3>What is Jitter Clicking?</h3>
    <p>Jitter clicking involves intentionally tensing the muscles in your arm and wrist to create rapid involuntary vibrations in your hand. These vibrations cause your clicking finger to bounce up and down on the mouse button much faster than deliberate individual clicks. Skilled jitter clickers achieve 10–15 CPS, with some reaching 16+ CPS in optimal conditions.</p>

    <h3>How to Start Jitter Clicking — Step by Step</h3>
    <p><strong>Step 1:</strong> Place your hand on your mouse normally. <strong>Step 2:</strong> Tense your forearm and wrist muscles — like you're vibrating your hand. Start gently; don't strain. <strong>Step 3:</strong> While tensed, let your index finger rest on the mouse button with light contact. The vibration should cause it to click rapidly. <strong>Step 4:</strong> Gradually increase the tension to increase speed while maintaining control. It takes 2–4 weeks of daily practice to jitter click reliably.</p>

    <h3>Is Jitter Clicking Safe?</h3>
    <p>Jitter clicking causes arm fatigue and, with excessive use, can contribute to repetitive strain injuries. Limit jitter clicking sessions to 10–15 minutes and stop immediately if you feel pain. Many experienced jitter clickers alternate between jitter and regular clicking to reduce strain.</p>

    <h3>Jitter Clicking vs Butterfly Clicking</h3>
    <p>Butterfly clicking uses two fingers alternating on one button and is generally less physically demanding than jitter clicking while achieving similar or higher CPS. If you're new to advanced clicking techniques, some players find butterfly clicking more sustainable long-term. Try both on our tests and see which comes more naturally to you.</p>

    <h3>Is Jitter Clicking Allowed on Servers?</h3>
    <p>Most Minecraft servers allow jitter clicking as long as your CPS stays within their anti-cheat limits (typically 14–16 CPS). However, reaching very high jitter CPS (18+) may trigger anti-cheat flags. Always check your server's specific rules before using jitter clicking in competitive play.</p>

